Serialization formats: Examples


XML
&lt;people&gt;
  &lt;person&gt;
    &lt;name&gt;Alice&lt;/name&gt;
    &lt;age&gt;30&lt;/age&gt;
    &lt;hobbies&gt;
      &lt;hobby&gt;reading&lt;/hobby&gt;
      &lt;hobby&gt;cycling&lt;/hobby&gt;
    &lt;/hobbies&gt;
  &lt;/person&gt;
  &lt;person&gt;
    &lt;name&gt;Bob&lt;/name&gt;
    &lt;age&gt;25&lt;/age&gt;
    &lt;hobbies&gt;
      &lt;hobby&gt;gaming&lt;/hobby&gt;
    &lt;/hobbies&gt;
  &lt;/person&gt;
&lt;/people&gt;
Everything is a , tags are nested, closing tags with &lt;/tag&gt; are required

JSON
[
  {
    "name": "Alice",
    "age": 30,
    "hobbies": ["reading", "cycling"]
  },
  {
    "name": "Bob",
    "age": 25,
    "hobbies": ["gaming"]
  }
]
[] define lists, {} define objects, : separates keys and values, , separates items in lists and objects, indentation is not relevant

YAML
- name: Alice
  age: 30
  hobbies:
    - reading
    - cycling
- name: Bob
  age: 25
  hobbies:
    - gaming
- defines list items, indentation defines structure, : separates keys and values

